So last Friday was an end to my awesome experience at Cvent. It is said that the first job's experience, learning, and connections are incomparable and I am glad to have Cvent as that stepping stone for me.

A year ago, when I stepped into the Cvent's office, I never thought I'll end up with all the great opportunities, experiences, friendships, amazing colleagues, and growth that I have undergone here!

From debugging issues that occurred in some of the biggest events worldwide to training and preparing the new generation of interns, all the way through while spending time working on developing Cvent's internal Node.js and Angular.js projects. Discovering my ability to handle high pressure by hopping onto onsite issues and providing creative resolutions on a high priority basis and also developing javascript codes to handle high dollar value client's issues. I was awarded, inspired, humbled, and continued to feel immense gratitude for the path I've had the opportunity to tread. 

It was great to participate in Cvent's Annual Hackathon and compete with the greatest minds of Tech globally. Exhilaratingly, our team was awarded the first position.

Looking to learn Nodejs?

How about starting by learning the following 5 things?

1. The Javascript standard ECMAScript: learning this will help you understand what JS features are supported in your Nodejs version and what is not. 
2. The languages in which you can write Nodejs applications. Namely Javascript or Typescript.
3. The Observer pattern, as Nodejs applications heavily rely on this design pattern.
4. The Callback pattern which supplements the Observer pattern in carrying out executions.
5. Basics of the V8 engine and how it executes the Javascript code that you write. It's important not to go too deep into this has it can be quite complex to understand at first.

What is the concurrent mode in react?


React is continuously adding new powerful features to its core API‚Äôs and speedily adapting to a better way of programming. Last time the react team came up with the hooks which are a cool and smart feature for functional programming. Now its time for introducing concurrency in react!
So what is concurrency at all?
If you start searching in google you can see thousands of examples and definitions for concurrency in computer-science, many of them play around with the classical dining philosopher problem. But in our case react is going to solve a very simple problem that modern JavaScript libraries haven‚Äôt addressed yet.
The non-blocking rendering
Typically the modern UI libraries do not support interrupting the rendering process. This is called the blocking rendering, now react is going to make it non-blocking. That is the rendering is Interruptible.

#Serverless chat app practice. As I'm learning more about about serverless technologies I admit was completely unaware of the power/potential of ApiGateway, it does a lot of heavy lifting. The best example of this i've seen (so far) has been with the creation of 
hashtag
#websocket 
hashtag
#api which simply facilitate real time connections & messages back and forth between connected users. I came across an implementation written in 
hashtag
#javascript and wanted to gain more familiarity, so I put this one together in 
hashtag
#python. Without going too much into the weeds, the lambda functions are triggered when a client connects to the websocket, api gateway provides a connection id for the session, which is stored in 
hashtag
#dynamodb. Once connected, a user enters a text message using the correct syntax, and this message is pushed to all connected clients in real time, because the connection ids are stored and fetched from the database (I think that's so clever). API gateway manages the connections and triggers lambda functions which facilitates the sending of messages between all connected users...just a basic chat application. Thanks 
hashtag
#Stackoverflow for helping me debug that 
hashtag
#ForbiddenException error.
